<page_title>Thermal Conductivity Experiments</page_title>
<text>Thermal Conductivity Experiments

What happens when blocks of atoms share KE?

This model has groups of purple and blue atoms. The purple ones have lots of kinetic energy, as you can see by checking the &quot;K.E. Shading&quot; button. The graph shows the average KE of the purple and blue atoms separately. Turn on the K.E. shading.  When you run the model, you can see what happens to the KE.


   
 

This experiment starts with two identical solids, except one has more KE than the other.

How slowly can you reach equilibrium? Experiment with removing some of the atoms between the two kinds. Construct a new structure that warms even more slowly.

 

 

The average KE is the temperature. 

This model shows that energy flows from a region of high KE to a region of low KE until the kinetic energy is equalized.
Heat flows from hot to cold. 
This is why we can identify temperature as the average kinetic energy.

    </text>
